 The role of overlapping attributes in group construal</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/E005470/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>This research examines the role of overlapping and distinct traits in social stereotypes.&amp;nbsp; Research conducted over the past years has demonstrated that the way in which relations between groups impact on the content of stereotypes, such that co-operative or positively interdependent relationships lead to an increased use of overlapping traits, while competitive or negatively interdependent relationships lead to more distinct traits being used. It has also been demonstrated that this differential accessibility of overlapping traits was transmitted via communication and had consequences for inter-group discrimination.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>The prime purpose of this PDF is to disseminate these findings and their implications to a broad audience. Papers will be submitted to top-end international journals; and the main conclusions communicated to academic and non-academic audiences via other channels. During this PDF, Dr.&amp;nbsp; Dora Bernardes will work with Prof. Spears, currently a key figure in the field of social identity, inter-group relations and stereotyping. Together with Prof. Spears and Prof. Postmes the importance of social identity based functions underlying the representation of groups in terms of overlapping/differentiating traits will be investigated. The grant will employ a number of techniques that will differentially encourage the use of either overlapping or differentiating traits to explore our account that stereotypes are organically emergent construals.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2007-09-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2007-01-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>51086</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications/><gtr:identifiers><gtr:identifier type="RCUK">ES/E005470/1</gtr:identifier></gtr:identifiers><gtr:healthCategories/><gtr:researchActivities/><gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>5D762B83-597E-4E91-B2F7-04CBB955175C</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Pol. sci. &amp; internat. studies</gtr